Hi Everyone,It seems that Google has changed the way they are allowing us to interact with the Maps API. In order for the app to start working, you need to get your own API Developer key and put it into your code. Here are the steps to doing this:1. Find and open the file UCSDGraphs/src/html/index.html in a text editor. Do not open this file in a web browser. You must open it for editing in a text editor of your choice like Notepad, Notepad++, SimpleText, Sublime, etc. 2. Replace ALL OF the code in that file with the following code: <!DOCTYPE html> <html> <head> <title>Simple Map!</title> <meta name="viewport" content="initial-scale=1.0"> <meta charset="utf-8"> <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="routing.css" /> </head> <body> <!----<div id="directions-panel"></div> --> <div id="map"></div> <!--- You must get your own API Key and insert it in the line below where it says [APIKeyHere] for this to work. You can find instructions for doing this in the starter code setup guide or just try it on your own by going to https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/ and clicking "Get a Key". --> <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=[APIKeyHere]&callback=initMap"></script> <script type="text/javascript" src="visual.js"></script> </body> </html> Save the file but keep the text editor open. You'll make another change to this code shortly. 3. Follow the instructions in Part 2: Obtain and use your Google Maps API Javascript Developer Key in the new Starter Code Setup Guide. After that things should run again. Please let us know if this fix solves the problem.

<co-content><text>Hi Ayder...</text><text>This is a great question.  One of the problems with A* is that it can get stuck, like it does in your example.  Nice example, by the way.</text><text>There are several modifications to the search algorithm that may help find the correct answer.  Two that I have used are the 2-Opt and the Genetic algorithms.</text><text>In the 2-Opt algorithm, you start with the shortest paths between all points (matrix).  You can use the repetitive nearest neighbour algorithm.  Then, you swap pairs of vertices (all except the starting vertex) to see if you obtain a shorter path.  Other options allow you to swap more than 2 vertices at a time.  Note that this algorithm can also be used to help solve the Traveling Salesperson problem.  This is probably your best bet for solving your problem.</text><text>The genetic algorithm is used to solve the TSP problem (where all locations are visited only once, returning to the starting point).  This is probably not applicable to your example, as not all vertices are visited, but it is a very interesting solution to the TSP that you may wish to investigate further (I had a lot of fun with it)!</text><text>Hope this helps!</text><text>Paul</text></co-content>
